r decisions reflected the demands of the ruling class. He shows that conflicting interests of fractions of the ruling class and foreign investors gradually led to far greater state participation than any of the participants originally desired, and that the structure of the economy and of society—not the intentions of the actors—best explains the state’s economic presence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBrazil-Economic policy. 0aBrazil-History-1889-1930. 0aCoffee industry-Brazil-History. 0aFinance-History-Brazil. 0aRailroads-Brazil-History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76500940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477305195423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477305195/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK